Why not just roll them into one suite?

package com.terraspring.hh.util;

import junit.framework.*;

public class AllTests {

     public static Test suite() {
         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
         suite.addTestSuite(SupplierTest.class);
         suite.addTestSuite(ConsumerTest.class);
         return suite;
     }
}

On Tuesday, October 8, 2002, at 03:44 PM, Steven Taschuk wrote:

&gt; Quoth ktbarrett:
&gt;&gt; I am trying to run more than one JUnit test from Ant which shares
&gt;&gt; some static data through the VM. The following is an excerpt from my
&gt;&gt; Ant script.
&gt;   [...]
&gt;&gt; The problem is, the VM seems to fork whether I tell it too or not. My
&gt;&gt; first test (SupplierTest) is creating some static objects, and my
&gt;&gt; second test (ConsumerTest) is trying to use those objects. The
&gt;&gt; problem is that either Ant is creating a new VM or a new ClassLoader
&gt;&gt; so my data is not available.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Any ideas?
&gt;
&gt; First, have you tried the following?
&gt; 	&lt;target name=&quot;test&quot;&gt;
&gt; 		&lt;junit fork=&quot;no&quot;&gt;
&gt; 			&lt;test name=&quot;SupplierTest&quot;/&gt;
&gt; 			&lt;test name=&quot;ConsumerTest&quot;/&gt;
&gt; 		&lt;/junit&gt;
&gt; 	&lt;/target&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Second, a quick glance through the Ant 1.4.1 source makes me think
&gt; Ant doesn&#39;t make a new VM if you say fork=&#39;no&#39;, but it does make
&gt; its own ClassLoader regardless.  (Note that the &lt;junit&gt; task
&gt; supports a nested &lt;classpath&gt; element, so I imagine this is
&gt; necessary.)  I encourage you to study the source for more
&gt; information, or to inquire on the Ant mailing list (which I assume
&gt; to exist).  And you could always write your own Ant task if the
&gt; out-of-the-box behaviour is not what you want.
&gt;
&gt; Third, is it possible your objects are being garbage-collected
&gt; between the tests?
&gt;
&gt; Finally, it is usually considered desirable that tests not
&gt; interact with one another.  It might be best to either (a) unify
&gt; the two tests to use the same test fixture, or (b) to make the
&gt; latter test do its own set up so it doesn&#39;t depend on the former
&gt; being run.  What&#39;s the motivation for the inter-test dependency?
